						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">ibeenew2 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">clueless wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I am after the same, but for MMC1.</div><br /><br />usb copynes + powerpak lite, done</div>
<br />
<br />I would prefer to not dissemble my NES and extract the CPU.
<br />
<br />I've read the threads about alternate mappers that Tepples point out.  I'm all for a new mapper.  I don't need a strictly conforming MMC1, MMC3 or FME7.
<br />
<br />One thing that I don't like about MMC1 is that there is only one switchable ROM bank.  I like the idea of having a small switchable ROM bank for holding music samples.  Something that the NMI handler can have free reign over without clobbering what the main thread is doing.
<br />
<br />I'd like to animate background tiles and sprites (for water / shoreline effects like in Crystalis (MMC3 btw)).  Since right now I'm restricting myself to MMC1, I've opted to use non-switching CHR-RAM.  So I can animate very few tiles at a time, but its workable.
<br />
<br />I want to have 8-way background scrolling.  I'm willing to live with scroll artifacts on the edges if I must, but like most people, would prefer to avoid them.
<br />
<br />I need a ~2 row status bar.  I've put mine at the top and use sprite-0 hits to switch nametables.  I'm ok with this, but if there is a better way (like, say, an IRQ), then I'd like that instead.  Waiting for sprite-0 wastes a lot of CPU cycles.
<br />
<br />I want the 8K of RAM from $6000-$7fff.  Atleast 1K battery backed.  
<br />
<br />Heck, if the 8K of RAM could be bankable too then that would be awesome.  I could do some really interesting things with deformable terrain if I had more RAM.
<br />
<br />ps- Tepples / Memblers, How would your theoretical mapper detect that the PPU is trying to render tile $FF?  What is it looking for at the wire level?</div>

