					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I like CopyNES, but frankly the software sucks if you use it exclusively for quick tests for development (while being great for dumping carts, mapper testing, even emulating and single-stepping through the code, on the NES CPU itself).  What I've hoped to see is a command-line app that will upload (user specifies the plugin and ROM file), then enter play mode.  I noticed people were supporting CopyNES in linux, it would be nice if that sort of functionality ever showed up in an app such as ucon64.  I haven't been following it much though.
<br />
<br />The 2nd thread tepples linked to is my idea for a flash cart, I think it's better than MMC1.  There is no IRQ, 2 16kB PRG pages, 2 2kB CHR pages (other 2kB halves are fixed), h/v/1 mirroring select register, optional 32kB WRAM.  Logic fits in a 36-macrocell CPLD.  The hope is to make it cheap enough to use it for releasing games.  And as a cheap flashcart, why not buy several, and share your games/demos/music with friends, heheh.   CopyNES could program it even if it was 100% erased.   The expansion port adapter I'm working on (with some great help from Xious) and virtually any adapter, could program it using the bootloader discussed in this thread.  The Verilog is ready, I need to do a good board layout for it, but I've sorta jumped onto getting this expansion device working because it'll make it a lot more interesting.
<br />
<br />The expansion port adapter could support IRQ (and I believe NMI, as well!).  Obviously that's only any use if you have the expansion hardware though.  But I'm hoping the sound capabilities, file saving/loading, and other features will make it pretty interesting.</div>

